Today, I will introduce my first bill in Congress -- the Service, Training, Education, and Preparation (STEP) for Veterans Act. I'm excited to be up in northern and central Nevada for a district listening tour. The 4th Congressional District is one of the most diverse in the country- urban and rural, White, African American, Hispanic, and Asian, military, veterans, and civilians, stretching from Las Vegas to Ely. As I work to best represent my constituents, I could think of no better way of learning about their issues than coming directly to them. I look forward to hearing more about needs of the district to better carry their voices to Washington, D.C.   Follow all the action on Twitter: @RepKihuen #CD4Tour

President Trump’s proposed budget will place a nuclear waste repository at Yucca Mountain. This administration plans to build a nuclear waste repository in our backyard, endangering the health and wellness of the people of Nevada. I urge President Trump and Secretary Perry to reconsider this dangerous plan of action. The Nevada delegation was united in sponsoring the Nuclear Waste Informed Consent Act earlier this year, demanding that states be consulted before nuclear waste repositories can be built by the federal government.  We need to ensure that federal tax dollars are spent in the best interest of American citizens, not in ways that threaten the state of Nevada.

This morning, I testified before a hearing of the House Subcommittee on Environment, Committee on Energy and Commerce, opposing the use of Yucca Mountain as a Nuclear repository. Yucca Mountain is only 90 miles from Las Vegas and puts the safety of Nevadans at risk. I have serious concerns about this proposal -- from the transportation of nuclear materials to the risk of seismic activity that could cause leaching of nuclear material into the aquifer around Yucca Mountain – and will continue to fight to keep Nevadans safe.
If other states think Nevada will be the dumping ground for their nuclear waste - they've got another thing coming.
If this was proposed in your district—near your family—and threatened your constituents lives and jobs, would you support it? If the answer is yes, then let’s find a place in your district.

The fight to protect our care isn't over. The Graham-Cassidy-Heller-Johnson bill will slash Nevada's federal funding for health care by $2.7 billion. The Graham-Cassidy-Heller-Johnson bill would also gut key provisions of the Affordable Care Act like rules prohibiting higher premiums for those with pre-existing conditions. Every day, my staff provides assistance to constituents going through the federal agency claims and benefits process.  Mr. Burrell contacted our office because a decision on his disability claims covering four years was delayed and he was awaiting a decision. Our staff reached out to the Department of Veterans Affairs to find out what information was needed to make a decision on his payments and then worked with Mr. Burrell, assisting him in providing the necessary documentation. Once the Department of Veterans Affairs had the information needed, they made a decision to increase Mr. Burrell’s disability compensation, and Mr. Burrell received $152,080 in retroactive payments.  Reach out to our office to contact a member of our staff! www.kihuen.house.gov
